result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Court review plea questionnaire with defendant, waiver of constitutional rights and elements of the crime plead to.  Defendant said he understood.  Court finds that the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.

ADA Inlow appeared on behalf of the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Betthauser.  Defendant plead no contest to count 1.  Count 2 dismissed and read in.  Diversion agreement entered into on count 1.  Court reviewed the conditions of the diversion agreement with the defendant.  Defendant says he understands his obligations under the diversion agreement and will be able to comply fully. Attorney Betthauser believes the defendant understands the agreement.   Minimum of a 12 month diversion agreement.  Attorney Betthauser stipulated to a factual basis.  Factual basis found.  Diversion agreement approved by the court.

Pre-trial conference at 03-04-2015 10:00 am.
Status conference at 03-23-2015 03:00 pm.

ADA Inlow appeared on behalf of the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Betthauser.  Reading of complaint waived, defendant stood mute to the charges.  NGP entered on defendant's behalf.  Bond amended.  PTC & STC set.

Defendant shall not consume any alcohol unless a physician states in writing that the defendant is alcohol dependent and complete withdrawal could endanger the defendant's health or life. In this case a doctor's excuse must be submitted to the Jackson County Clerk of Court or the Jackson County Jail within 48 hours of the bond being signed. Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, bar areas of restaurants, or where available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located. Except for employment purposes only in his own establishment.   As a condition of your release, you must be available 24 hours per day, 7 days a week to submit to testing for alcohol when requested by a law enforcement officer or your probation agent. The defendant may submit to an alcohol test at the Jackson County Sheriff's Office or submit to a PBT by a law enforcement officer. Upon request, the defendant shall appear for and submit to testing within two (2) hours of the official's request.
